<H2 align=3Dcenter><FONT color=3Dmaroon>Open Document Management API <A=20
name=3Dspec>Version 1.0a</FONT></H2>
<CENTER></CENTER>
<P>
<BLOCKQUOTE><BR>Revision history:<BR>
  <P>
  <UL>
    <LI>Version 1.0 - with small BHC 325 at the end of the =
document<BR>Brad=20
    Clements. This is the original version.<BR>
    <P></P>
    <LI>Version 1.0 - with small DM1\285 at the end of the =
document<BR>Mike=20
    Gardiner. This contains additional information for registering ODMA =
under=20
    Windows 95 and NT. It also adds a new table for document ID =
constants.<BR>
    <P></P>
    <LI>Version 1.0a<BR>Rod Schiffman. Additional information on the =
ODMA spec=20
    background, usage of calls, <BR>suggestions on the use of document =
ID=20
    character sets and the addition of ODM_E_INUSE as a valid return =
code in=20
    ODMActivate.=20
    <P>
    <HR>

    <P>The purpose of this update to the ODMA specification is to =
clarify a=20
    number of issues that have been raised by companies that have =
implemented=20
    ODMA in their products. It does not change any of the calls or=20
    functionality. It is a preliminary step to creating the next version =
of the=20
    specification. There is additional information about the usage of =
the calls,=20
    as well as more information about the goals of ODMA. The document, =
perhaps=20
    even more than in the past, retains an informal writing style. </P>
    <P>The original impetus for ODMA was the recognition that there was =
no=20
    standard method for a client application to integrate with a DMS. =
Each DMS=20
    vendor wrote separate integration code for each of the major client=20
    applications they supported. Applications that did not have =
integrations=20
    written for them by the DMS vendors would have to write and support =
a=20
    separate integration for each DMS that was supported. This required =
a=20
    complete matrix of integrations, each with its own set of bugs, =
limitations=20
    and reliability issues. It seemed obvious that a high level standard =
for=20
    connecting applications and document management systems was a =
natural fit. A=20
    small group of application and DMS vendors started working together =
to=20
    create an API that would allow applications and document management =
systems=20
    to inter-operate through a single high level API. This implied the =
creation=20
    of a standard, however, the creation of a standard has many =
pitfalls.=20
    Probably the biggest problem is that a lot of work can be put into =
the=20
    creation of the standard, and nobody uses it. </P>
    <P>The industry is filled with examples of standards that were =
obsolete by=20
    the time they made it through the standardization process. By time =
some=20
    standards make it through the standardization process, they are so =
large and=20
    unwieldy they are almost impossible to implement and maintain. =
Company=20
    politics and hidden agendas of the participants can play as big a =
role in=20
    the adoption of a standard as trying to solve the problem in the =
first=20
    place. The industry is also full of proprietary API=92s that claim =
to be=20
    standards, but are not. The initial group of vendors that met and =
formed the=20
    ODMA consortium wanted to avoid as many of these problems as =
possible.</P>
    <H4><FONT color=3Dmaroon>The working rules of the ODMA consortium =
are fairly=20
    simple.</FONT> </H4>
    <OL>
      <LI>If the standard does not solve a problem it will not be used.=20
      <LI>If the creation of the standard takes a long period of time, =
it does=20
      not solve the problem.=20
      <LI>If the standard is difficult to implement, it does not solve =
the=20
      problem.=20
      <LI>The standard must be vendor independent.=20
      <LI>The standard must not try to solve all vendors problems, or it =
will be=20
      big, complex and take a long time to implement. This violates =
rules 1, 2=20
      and 3 above.=20
      <LI>It is the customers that lose if there is not a =
straightforward way to=20
      integrate applications that create documents, and applications =
that manage=20
      documents. Easy integration between applications and document =
management=20
      systems will grow the industry and increase sales for the entire=20
      marketplace. </LI></OL>
    <P>It is difficult to express the importance the initial members of =
the=20
    consortium placed on wanting to create a useful API that is vendor =
and=20
    platform independent while still simple to implement. They =
recognized that=20
    they could solve 80 percent of the problem easily and were willing =
to live=20
    with having to solve another 10 percent over time and probably never =
being=20
    able to solve the final 10 percent. </P>
    <P>The Open Document Management API (ODMA) is a standardized, =
high-level=20
    interface between desktop applications and document management =
systems=20
    (DMSs). </P>
    <H4><FONT color=3Dmaroon>Its purposes are: </FONT></H4>
    <OL>
      <LI><FONT face=3D"Times New Roman">To make DMS services available =
to users=20
      of desktop application in a seamless manner so that these services =
appear=20
      to the user like extensions of the applications. </FONT>
      <LI><FONT face=3D"Times New Roman">To reduce the application =
vendors' burden=20
      of having to deal with multiple DMS vendors. By writing to ODMA, =
an=20
      application vendor has potentially integrated his application with =
all=20
      supporting DMSs. </FONT>
      <LI><FONT face=3D"Times New Roman">To reduce the DMS vendors' =
burden of=20
      integrating with multiple applications. By supporting ODMA a DMS =
vendor=20
      has potentially integrated with all applications that have written =
to=20
      ODMA. </FONT>
      <LI><FONT face=3D"Times New Roman">To reduce effort and complexity =
needed to=20
      install and maintain DMSs. </FONT></LI></OL>
    <P>ODMA specifies a set of interfaces that applications can use to =
initiate=20
    actions within a DMS. The API is intended to be relatively easy for=20
    application vendors to incorporate into updates of existing =
applications. It=20
    should not require major restructuring of an application to =
integrate it=20
    with ODMA. Note that this version of ODMA does not specify how DMSs =
may=20
    initiate actions within the applications. </P>
    <P>The ODMA API is platform-independent. The associated data type=20
    definitions and binding information are platform-specific. =
Currently, most=20
    of the work has been done in Windows. It makes this document look =
Windows=20
    specific, but over time, the platform specific entries for other =
platforms=20
    will be added as they are defined. </P>
    <H4><FONT color=3Dmaroon>Document IDs </FONT></H4>
    <P>Many of the ODMA functions accept or return a Document ID =
parameter. A=20
    document ID is a persistent, portable identifier for a document. It =
can be=20
    stored and used in a later session, and it can be passed across =
platforms=20
    via email or other processes. </P>
    <P>Document IDs are case insensitive, null-terminated strings of =
printable=20
    characters. Although a document ID is case insensitive, an =
application=20
    should never change the case of a document ID. The format of a =
document ID=20
    is </P>
    <CENTER>
    <H4 align=3Dcenter>::ODMA\DM_ID\DM_SPECIFIC_INFO </H4></CENTER>
    <P>The DM_ID portion of a document ID will identify which DMS =
provided the=20
    ID. This information is primarily for the use of ODMA itself; =
applications=20
    using ODMA should not need to know which DMS provided a particular =
ID. The=20
    ODMA group members will coordinate these IDs to ensure their =
uniqueness. The=20
    maximum length of the DM_ID portion of the document ID is specified =
by the=20
    constant <B>ODM_DMSID_MAX. </B></P>
    <P>The DM_SPECIFIC_INFO portion of the ID will vary depending on =
which DMS=20
    built the ID. The total length of the document ID including the =
terminating=20
    Null character cannot exceed <B>ODM_DOCID_MAX</B> bytes. </P>
    <P>ODMA-aware applications should be able to handle a document ID =
anywhere=20
    they handle an externally-generated document filename. For example, =
if the=20
    application allows a document filename to be passed as a command =
line=20
    argument then it should allow a document ID to be passed in the same =
way. If=20
    the application allows document filenames to be used in DDE commands =
then it=20
    should also support the use of document IDs in the same commands. =
</P>
    <P>Although the technical definition of a document ID is a case =
insensitive,=20
    null-terminated strings of printable characters, there are some =
general=20
    rules that are more likely to make a DMS and ODMA application work =
better=20
    together. ODMA was designed so that it would be easy to add to an=20
    application without major modifications in code or structure. If a =
DMS=20
    passes a document ID that breaks fundamental rules of normal file =
and path=20
    names it will probably run into problems if it is passed in on a =
command=20
    line. Special characters like ^, [, ], |, *, -, &gt;, &lt; and ? are =

    processed by the Unix shell even before they are seen by the =
application. It=20
    is possible to pass these characters by using special escape =
sequences, but=20
    that places a burden on the DMS vendor to process the document ID =
before=20
    giving it to the ODMA application. Some operating systems require =
the=20
    application to handle the reverse process of interpreting and =
removing the=20
    escape characters. The application may be able to support the escape =
removal=20
    on the command line, but not if the document ID with escape =
characters is=20
    returned in a procedure call. In most cases, it is easier to =
generate a=20
    document ID that contains a fairly simple set of characters. The =
following=20
    table suggests characters it may be wise to avoid for different=20
    platforms.<BR>
    <TABLE border=3D2 cellPadding=3D3 cellSpacing=3D2>
      <TBODY>
      <TR>
        <TD><B><FONT size=3D4>Platform</B></FONT></TD>
        <TD><B><FONT size=3D4>Characters to =
Avoid</B></FONT></TD></TR><BR>
      <TR>
        <TD>Windows 3.x</TD>
        <TD>" ' &lt; &gt; * ? | and the space character</TD></TR><BR>
      <TR>
        <TD>Windows 95</TD>
        <TD>" ' &lt; &gt; * ? |</TD></TR><BR>
      <TR>
        <TD>Other platforms to be defined</TD>
        <TD></TD></TR><BR></TBODY></TABLE><BR>
    <H4><FONT color=3Dmaroon>Constants</FONT></H4>
    <P>
    <TABLE border=3D2 cellPadding=3D3 cellSpacing=3D2>
      <TBODY>
      <TR>
        <TD><B><FONT size=3D4>CONSTANTS</FONT></B></TD>
        <TD>Windows 3.x</TD>
