    <H4><FONT color=3Dmaroon>Error Handling</FONT> </H4>
    <P>Nearly all of the ODMA functions use the return value to indicate =
to the=20
    calling application whether the function succeeded, failed because =
the user=20
    canceled the operation, or failed for other reasons. The DMS is =
responsible=20
    for displaying informational error messages to the user where =
appropriate=20
    except when the ODM_SILENT flag is specified. The DMS must take care =
to=20
    return the appropriate error indication because applications may act =

    differently depending on whether an ODMA call was canceled by the =
user or=20
    failed for other reasons. The calling application generally should =
not=20
    display error messages when an error value is returned from ODMA =
unless the=20
    ODM_SILENT flag was specified. </P>
    <H4><FONT color=3Dmaroon>Connections and the ODMA Connection =
Manager</FONT>=20
    </H4>
    <P>The ODMA connection manager is a small software module that sits =
between=20
    applications using ODMA and document management systems implementing =
ODMA.=20
    It manages the connections between these components and routes ODMA =
calls to=20
    the appropriate provider. A freely-redistributable copy of the ODMA=20
    connection manager will be provided to any vendor wishing to =
implement or=20
    make use of the ODMA API. This is a place where it would be possible =
to=20
    provide mapping code that would allow ODMA to have truly platform=20
    independent document IDs, however, it currently only manages =
connections and=20
    does not touch document IDs. </P>
    <H4><FONT color=3Dmaroon>Document Format Names</FONT> </H4>
    <P>When new documents are registered with a DMS via ODMA and when an =

    existing document's format is changed by an application, the =
application=20
    passes a document format name to ODMA. Document format names are=20
    Null-terminated strings defining the format of a document's content. =

    Application vendors are encouraged to make public the format names =
they=20
    choose for their proprietary formats so that other ODMA users and =
providers=20
    can standardize on the same names. The odma.h header file contains =
names for=20
    common, non-proprietary formats such as text, RTF, and TIFF. This is =
a=20
    significant limitation in the ODMA 1.0 specification. There is a =
proposal in=20
    an appendix at the end of this document to create a standardization =
for=20
    document format names under Windows. </P>
    <H4><FONT color=3Dmaroon>Character Sets </FONT></H4>
    <P>All strings passed to or returned from ODMA functions should be =
in the=20
    native character set of the system on which ODMA is being used. So =
for=20
    example, 8859-1 would be used on English Windows, Shift-JIS would be =
used on=20
    Japanese Windows, Unicode would be used on NT, etc. The term=20
    "Null-terminated" as used in this specification means terminated by =
the=20
    character set's natural Null character. For most character sets this =
means a=20
    single byte with the value 0x0; for Unicode it means a sequence of 2 =
bytes=20
    with the value 0x0. If an application obtains an ODMA document ID on =
one=20
    platform and later uses it on another platform, the application is=20
    responsible for translating the ID to the native character set of =
the second=20
    platform before using it there. </P>
    <H4><FONT color=3Dmaroon>Application Interfaces</FONT> </H4>
    <P>An ODMA-aware application can choose to communicate with the ODMA =

    Connection Manager either through a traditional, function-oriented =
API or=20
    through Component Object Model (COM) interfaces. Prototypes and =
constants=20
    used for the function-oriented API are included in the odma.h header =
file.=20
    Prototypes, constants, and interface definitions for the COM =
interface are=20
    included in the odmacom.h header file. </P>
    <P>After calling ODMRegisterApp applications can obtain one or more =
COM=20
    interfaces to ODMA through the ODMQueryInterface function. The =
IODMDocMan=20
    interface provides an alternate entry point to most of the ODMA =
functions=20
    documented below. This interface and its interface ID are defined in =
the=20
    odmacom.h header file. </P>
    <P>Note that IODMDocMan::QueryInterface will only query the default =
DMS for=20
    the calling application. The application must call ODMQueryInterface =
in=20
    order to query other DMSs. </P>
    <H4><FONT color=3Dmaroon>ODMA API</FONT> </H4>
    <H3><FONT color=3Dmaroon>ODMRegisterApp </FONT></H3>
    <H5>ODMSTATUS ODMRegisterApp( ODMHANDLE FAR *pOdmHandle, WORD =
version, LPSTR=20
    lpszAppId, DWORD dwEnvData, LPVOID pReserved ) </H5>
    <P><B>ODMRegisterApp</B> registers an application with the =
appropriate=20
    Document Management System (DMS) and returns a handle that can be =
used in=20
    calls to other ODMA functions. An application must call this =
function before=20
    calling any of the other ODMA functions. A task may call=20
    <B>ODMRegisterApp</B> more than once; each call will return a =
different=20
    handle, each of which must be deregistered via =
<B>ODMUnRegisterApp</B>. </P>
    <H4><FONT color=3Dteal>Parameters:</FONT> </H4>
    <P><I>pOdmHandle</I> - out - If successful, a handle is returned =
here that=20
    can be used in calls to other ODMA functions. If the registration =
fails then=20
    0 is returned here. </P>
    <P><I>version - </I>in - Specifies the version of the API required =
by the=20
    application. 100 should be passed to indicate version 1.0, 110 =
should be=20
    passed to indicate version 1.1, etc. The macro =
<B>ODM_API_VERSION</B> can be=20
    used to get the correct version number at compile time. All versions =
of the=20
    ODMA API will be downward compatible, so this should be interpreted =
as the=20
    minimum version number that the calling application expects the DMS =
to=20
    support. If the DMS does not support the specified version or a =
higher=20
    version then it should return an error. </P>
    <P><I>lpszAppId</I> - in - A unique identifier for the application. =
The=20
    maximum length for this string is 16 characters including the =
terminating=20
    Null, and it cannot begin with a digit. It is recommended that a =
Windows=20
    application use the File Manager ProgId for its primary document =
class, but=20
    this is not required. </P>
    <P><I>dwEnvData</I> - in - Environment data. On Windows platforms =
this is a=20
    Window handle for a parent window in the calling application. The =
DMS may=20
    use this window handle as the parent window for any dialogs or other =
windows=20
    it displays in response to ODMA calls. This handle must remain valid =
for the=20
    duration of the ODMA session (i.e. until ODMUnRegisterApp is =
called). </P>
    <P><I>pReserved</I> - in - Reserved for future use. Must be set to =
Null.=20
</P>
    <P><B>Return value</B>: 0 is returned if successful. =
<B>ODM_E_NODMS</B> is=20
    returned if no Document Management System has been registered for =
the=20
    calling application. <B>ODM_E_CANTINIT</B> is returned if a DMS is=20
    registered for the calling application, but it fails to initialize =
itself.=20
    <B>ODM_E_VERSION</B> is returned if the DMS does not support the =
requested=20
    version of the API. </P>
    <H3><FONT color=3Dmaroon>ODMUnRegisterApp </FONT></H3>
    <P>void ODMUnRegisterApp( ODMHANDLE odmHandle ) <BR>An application =
that=20
    previously registered itself with a DMS via <B>ODMRegisterApp</B> =
should=20
    call this function when it is finished using the DMS. This would =
typically=20
    be done when the application is shutting down. After this call =
returns, the=20
    DMS handle is no longer valid and cannot be used for subsequent =
calls to=20
    ODMA functions. </P>
    <H4>Parameters: </H4>
    <P><I>odmHandle</I> - in - An ODMA handle obtained by a previous =
call to=20
    ODMRegisterApp. </P>
    <H3><FONT color=3Dmaroon>ODMSelectDoc</FONT> </H3>
    <H5>ODMSTATUS ODMSelectDoc( ODMHANDLE odmHandle, LPSTR lpszDocId, =
LPDWORD=20
    pdwFlags ) </H5>
    <P>This function causes the DMS to return a document ID representing =
a=20
    document that has been selected for some action. Typically the DMS =
will=20
    display searching and other dialogs that allow the user to =
interactively=20
    select a document from among those managed by the DMS. An =
application would=20
    typically call this function whenever the user needs to select a =
document to=20
    be opened or imported. </P>
    <H4><FONT color=3Dteal>Parameters:</FONT> </H4>
    <P><I>odmHandle</I> - in - An ODMA handle obtained by a previous =
call to=20
    <B>ODMRegisterAp</B><B>p</B>. </P>
    <P><I>lpszDocId</I> - out - A pointer to a buffer where the DMS will =
return=20
    the ID of the document selected by the user. This buffer needs to be =
at=20
    least ODM_DOCID_MAX bytes in length. If successful then a =
null-terminated=20
    document ID will be returned here. Otherwise the contents of the =
buffer will=20
    be undefined. </P>
    <P><I>pdwFlags</I> - in/out - On input, 0 or a combination of 1 or =
more of=20
    the following values: </P>
    <UL>
      <LI><B>ODM_SILENT</B> - The DMS should not require user =
interaction while=20
      satisfying the call. If the call cannot be satisfied without user=20
      interaction then an error should be returned. </LI></UL>
    <P>Upon return, one of the following flags will be set unless an =
error=20
    occurred: </P>
    <UL>
      <LI><B>ODM_MODIFYMODE </B>- The user indicated that the selected =
document=20
      should be opened in a modifiable mode.=20
      <LI><B>ODM_VIEWMODE</B> - The user indicated that the selected =
document=20
      should be opened in a view-only mode. </LI></UL>
    <P>Return value: 0 if successful. <B>ODM_E_CANCEL</B> if the user =
does not=20
    make a selection. <B>ODM_E_APPSELECT</B> if the user indicated that =
he wants=20
    to make a selection using the application's regular file selection=20
    facilities rather than using the DMS. In this case the application =
should=20
    just display its regular selection dialog as though ODMA were not =
present.=20
    <B>ODM_E_OTHERAPP</B> if the user selected a document from a =
different=20
    application; generally the caller should treat this the same as=20
    <B>ODM_E_CANCEL. ODM_E_USERINT</B> if the <B>ODM_SILENT</B> flag was =

    specified and the DMS could not make a selection without user =
interaction.=20
    <B>ODM_E_HANDLE</B> if <I>odmHandle</I> was invalid. </P>
    <P>In the case that ODM_E_APPSELECT is returned and a document is =
opened=20
    through the application's regular file selection facilities, the =
following=20
    behaviors are recommended: </P>
    <OL>
      <LI>File | Save and File | Close should be handled as though the =
DMS were=20
      not present.=20
      <LI>File | Save As should he handled through ODMA (specifically =
through=20
      the ODMSaveAs function). This will allow documents to be imported =
into the=20
      DMS. </LI></OL>
    <H4><FONT color=3Dmaroon>ODMOpenDoc</FONT> </H4>
    <H5>ODMSTATUS ODMOpenDoc( ODMHANDLE odmHandle, DWORD flags, LPSTR =
lpszDocId,=20
    LPSTR lpszDocLocation ) </H5>
    <P>This function causes the DMS to make a document available to the=20
    application. It performs any necessary pre-processing (mapping =
network=20
    drives, checking security, etc.) and then returns to the application =
a=20
    temporary filename that can be used to access the document during =
the=20
    current session. Note that this function does not open the document =
file; it=20
    merely makes the file temporarily available to the calling =
application. The=20
    application can then open, read, write, and close the file as =
needed. When=20
    the application is finished using the file, it should call=20
    <B>ODMCloseDoc.</B> </P>
    <P>If <B>ODM_MODIFYMODE</B> is requested, the DMS may refuse the =
request if=20
    the user has view-only rights or if the document is currently =
checked-out to=20
    another user. It is recommended that the application retry the =
request=20
    specifying <B>ODM_VIEWMODE</B> in this case so that the user can at =
least=20
    view the document. </P>
    <H4><FONT color=3Dteal>Parameters:</FONT> </H4>
    <P><I>odmHandle</I> - in - An ODMA handle obtained by a previous =
call to=20
    <B>ODMRegisterApp. </B></P>
    <P><I>flags</I> - in - One or more of the following flags: </P>
    <UL>
      <LI><B>ODM_MODIFYMODE</B> - The DMS should make the document =
available in=20
      a modifiable mode. This mode is assumed if <B>ODM_VIEWMODE</B> is =
not=20
      explicitly requested.=20
      <LI><B>ODM_VIEWMODE</B> - The DMS should make the document =
available in a=20
      view-only mode. Any changes made to the document will not be =
transferred=20
      back to the document repository. Note that it is invalid to =
specify both=20
      <B>ODM_VIEWMODE</B> and <B>ODM_MODIFYMODE</B> in the same call.=20
      <LI><B>ODM_SILENT</B> - The DMS should not require user =
interaction while=20
      satisfying the call. If the call cannot be satisfied without user=20
      interaction then an error should be returned. </LI></UL>
    <P><I>lpszDocId</I> - in - A document ID. This is typically obtained =
by a=20
    call to <B>ODMSelectDoc</B> or <B>ODMNewDoc.</B> </P>
    <P><I>lpszDocLocation</I> - out - A pointer to a buffer of at least=20
    <B>ODM_FILENAME_MAX</B> bytes in length. The DMS will store in this =
buffer a=20
    Null-terminated string indicating where the caller can access the =
document=20
    during the current session. Typically this will be the full =
path/file name=20
    of the specified document, but some document formats may dictate =
another=20
    type of location such as a directory name. If an error occurs then =
the=20
    contents of the buffer will be undefined. </P>
    <P><B>Return value</B>: 0 if successful. <B>ODM_E_ACCESS</B> if the =
user=20
    does not have the access rights requested (for example, modify mode =
was=20
    requested but the user only has view rights to the document).=20
    <B>ODM_E_INUSE</B> if the user is currently unable to access the =
document=20
    because it is checked out by another user; this differs from=20
    <B>ODM_E_ACCESS</B> in that it is expected that the user might be =
able to=20
    access the document in the specified mode at some point in the =
future.=20
    <B>ODM_E_DOCID</B> if the document ID is invalid or refers to a =
document=20
    that no longer exists. <B>ODM_E_USERINT</B> if the <B>ODM_SILENT</B> =
flag=20
    was specified and the DMS could not make the specified document =
available=20
    without user interaction. <B>ODM_E_FAIL</B> if the DMS is unable to =
make the=20
    document accessible for any other reason. <B>ODM_E_HANDLE</B> if=20
    <I>odmHandle</I> was invalid. </P>
    <H4><FONT color=3Dmaroon>ODMSaveDoc</FONT> </H4>
    <H5>ODMSTATUS ODMSaveDoc( ODMHandle odmHandle, LPSTR lpszDocId, =
LPSTR=20
    lpszNewDocId ) </H5>
    <P>This function tells the DMS that the document should be saved to =
the=20
    document repository. An application would typically call this =
function after=20
    saving changes to the temporary file returned by <B>ODMOpenDoc</B>. =
A new=20
    document ID is returned to the application which should be used for =
all=20
    subsequent operations on the document. This ID replaces the previous =

    document ID in the current session. The new ID may or may not be the =
same as=20
    the original ID. It will usually be the same unless the DMS saved =
the=20
    document as a new version or as a new document. If the new ID is =
different=20
    from the previous ID then the previous ID cannot be used =
subsequently=20
    without doing an <B>ODMOpenDoc</B> on it. </P>
    <H4><FONT color=3Dteal>Parameters:</FONT> </H4>
    <P><I>odmHandle</I> - in - An ODMA handle obtained by a previous =
call to=20
    <B>ODMRegisterApp</B>. </P>
    <P><I>lpszDocId</I> - in - A document ID. This is typically obtained =
by a=20
    call to <B>ODMSelectDoc</B> or <B>ODMNewDoc</B>. This document must =
have=20
    been previously opened in modify mode by a call to =
<B>ODMOpenDoc</B>. </P>
    <P><I>lpszNewDocId</I> - out - A pointer to a buffer where the DMS =
will=20
    return the new ID of the document. This buffer needs to be at least=20
    <B>ODM_DOCID_MAX</B> bytes in length. If successful then a =
null-terminated=20
    document ID will be returned here. Otherwise the contents of the =
buffer will=20
    be undefined. </P>
    <P><B>Return value</B>: 0 if successful. <B>ODM_E_OPENMODE</B> if =
the=20
    document was not previously opened in modifiable mode. =
<B>ODM_E_FAIL</B> if=20
    the DMS is unable to save the document to the document repository.=20
    <B>ODM_E_HANDLE</B> if odmHandle was invalid. </P>
    <H4><FONT color=3Dmaroon>ODMCloseDoc</FONT> </H4>
    <H5>ODMSTATUS ODMCloseDoc( ODMHANDLE odmHandle, LPSTR lpszDocId, =
DWORD=20
    activeTime, DWORD pagesPrinted, LPVOID sessionData, WORD dataLen ) =
</H5>
    <P>An application that has opened a document by calling =
<B>ODMOpenDoc</B>=20
    must call <B>ODMCloseDoc</B> when it is finished using the document. =
The=20
    application should not call this function until after it has closed =
the=20
    document, because the DMS may move the document or make it =
inaccessible as a=20
    result of this call. Note that this function will not cause the =
document to=20
    be saved into the DMS's persistent repository unless =
<B>ODMSaveDoc</B> has=20
    been called previously. </P>
    <H4><FONT color=3Dteal>Parameters</FONT>: </H4>
    <P><I>odmHandle</I> - in - An ODMA handle obtained by a previous =
call to=20
    <B>ODMRegisterApp</B>. </P>
    <P><I>lpszDocId</I> - in - A Null-terminated document ID. This is =
typically=20
    obtained by a call to <B>ODMSelectDoc</B> or =
<STRONG>ODMNewDoc</STRONG>.=20
    This document must have been previously opened by a call to=20
    <B>ODMOpenDoc</B>. </P>
    <P><I>activeTime</I> - in - If the application tracks time spent =
editing the=20
    document then it should pass the number of seconds here. Otherwise =
it should=20
    pass 0xFFFFFFFF. </P>
    <P><I>pagesPrinted</I> - in - If the application tracks the number =
of pages=20
    printed from this document during the current editing session, it =
should=20
    pass this number here. Otherwise it should pass 0xFFFFFFFF. </P>
    <P><I>sessionData</I> - in - The application may pass other =
information=20
    regarding the current editing session in this parameter. For =
example, an=20
    application might pass the number of keystrokes that were entered. =
The=20
    calling application is free to determine the format of this data, so =
DMSs=20
    that rely on this information will have to coordinate with each =
application=20
    supported. Null should be passed if the application has no =
meaningful=20
    information to pass through this parameter. </P>
    <P><I>dataLen </I>- in - The length of the data passed in the =
sessionData=20
    parameter. Ignored if sessionData is Null. </P>
    <P><B>Return value</B>: 0 if successful. <B>ODM_E_NOOPEN</B> if the =
document=20
    was not open. <B>ODM_E_HANDLE</B> if odmHandle was invalid. </P>
    <H4><FONT color=3Dmaroon>ODMNewDoc</FONT> </H4>
    <H5>ODMSTATUS ODMNewDoc( ODMHANDLE odmHandle, LPSTR lpszDocId, DWORD =

    dwFlags, LPSTR lpszFormat, LPSTR lpszDocLocation ) </H5>
    <P>This function causes the DMS to create a new document profile and =
return=20
    the document ID for the new document to the calling application. =
</P>
    <H4><FONT color=3Dteal>Parameters:</FONT> </H4>
    <P><I>odmHandle</I> - in - An ODMA handle obtained by a previous =
call=20
    to<B>ODMRegisterApp</B>.</P>
    <P><I>lpszDocId</I> - out - A pointer to a buffer where the DMS will =
return=20
    the ID of the document selected by the user. This buffer needs to be =
at=20
    least <B>ODM_DOCID_MAX</B> bytes in length. If successful then a=20
    Null-terminated document ID will be returned here. Otherwise the =
contents of=20
    the buffer will be undefined. </P>
    <P>dwFlags - in - 0 or a combination of 1 or more of the following =
values:=20
    </P>
    <UL>
      <LI><B>ODM_SILENT</B> - The DMS should not require user =
interaction while=20
      satisfying the call. If the call cannot be satisfied without user=20
      interaction then an error should be returned. </LI></UL>
    <P><I>lpszFormat</I> - in - A Null-terminated string naming the =
format of=20
    the new document's content. Note that this may be changed later via =
an=20
    ODMSaveAs call. </P>
    <P><I>lpszDocLocation</I> - in - Normally DMSs select the location =
for a new=20
    document. But if the document already exists and is large or resides =
on=20
    read-only storage then the calling application can use this =
parameter to=20
    tell the DMS where the document is currently stored. This is a hint =
to the=20
    DMS that the document should be left in this location. Note that =
some DMSs=20
    may ignore this hint and move the document anyway. The calling =
application=20
    should not directly access the document in this location following =
the call=20
    to <B>ODMNewDoc</B>; it should use <B>ODMOpenDoc</B> to obtain a =
location=20
    for subsequent access to the document. In most cases the application =
should=20
    pass Null in this parameter to allow the DMS to determine the =
document's=20
    storage location. </P>
    <P><B>Return value:</B> 0 if successful. <B>ODM_E_CANCEL</B> if the =
user=20
    cancels the creation of the new document. <B>ODM_E_FAIL</B> if the =
DMS=20
    failed to create the new document. <B>ODM_E_USERINT</B> if the=20
    <B>ODM_SILENT</B> flag was specified and the DMS could not make the=20
    specified document available without user interaction.=20
    <B>ODM_E_APPSELECT</B> if the user indicated that he wants to select =
the=20
    document's filename using the application's regular file selection=20
    facilities rather than using the DMS. In this case the application =
should=20
    just display its regular filename selection dialog as though ODMA =
were not=20
    present. <B>ODM_E_HANDLE</B> if odmHandle was invalid. </P>
    <H4><B><FONT color=3Dmaroon>ODMSaveAs </FONT></B></H4>
    <H5>ODMSTATUS ODMSaveAs( ODMHANDLE odmHandle, LPSTR lpszDocId, LPSTR =

    lpszNewDocId, LPSTR lpszFormat, ODMSAVEASCALLBACK pcbCallBack, =
LPVOID=20
    pInstanceData ) </H5>
    <P>This function causes the DMS to return a new document ID for a =
document=20
    that is based on an existing document. An application would =
typically call=20
    this function in response to the user selecting a SaveAs menu =
option.=20
    <B>ODMSaveAs</B> causes the DMS to display options to the user for =
selecting=20
    the destination for the new document. This might be an entirely new =
document=20
    or a new version of the current document. </P>
    <P>Often the application will want to present additional options to =
the user=20
    at this point such as different file formats or encrypting the =
document.=20
    This is accomplished via the pcbCallBack parameter. ODMA =
implementors should=20
    provide a method for users to access this function if desired. For =
example,=20
    the DMS may show a dialog that includes an Options button. If the =
user=20
    clicks this button, the DMS would call the application's callback =
function=20
    which would give the application a chance to display other save =
options.=20
</P>
    <P>Note that following a successful call to ODMSaveAs the calling=20
    application may have two different document IDs to work with. This =
is=20
    different than the situation with ODMSaveDoc where the new ID =
replaces the=20
    old one in the current session. The state of the document specified =
by the=20
    old ID remains the same after the call. The document specified by =
the new ID=20
    will be in the closed state following the call. A typical sequence =
of=20
    operations an application might follow in response to the user =
selecting=20
    File | Save As would be: </P>
    <UL>
      <LI>Application passes the currently open document's ID to =
ODMSaveAs. If=20
      Null is returned for the new ID then the sequence is complete. If =
a new ID=20
      for the document is returned then continue with the steps below.=20
      <LI>Application calls ODMOpenDoc on the new ID. This returns a new =

      filename for the document.=20
      <LI>Application saves the document to the new filename and then =
calls=20
      ODMSaveDoc on the new ID to indicate to the DMS that the new =
document=20
      should be saved in the document repository.=20
      <LI>Application calls ODMCloseDoc on the old ID.=20
      <LI>The application can now forget about the old ID and use the =
new ID for=20
      all subsequent operations on the file. When the current session is =

      completed it will call ODMCloseDoc on the new ID. </LI></UL>
    <P><FONT color=3Dteal>Parameters:</FONT> </P>
    <P><I>odmHandle</I> - in - An ODMA handle obtained by a previous =
call to=20
    <B>ODMRegisterApp.</B> </P>
    <P><I>lpszDocId</I> - in - A Null-terminated document ID. This is =
typically=20
    obtained by a call to <B>ODMSelectDoc</B> or <B>ODMNewDoc</B>. This =
document=20
    may or may not be open at the time that ODMSaveAs is called. Its =
open status=20
    will remain the same after this call. </P>
    <P><I>lpszNewDocId</I> - out - A pointer to a buffer where the DMS =
will=20
    return the ID of the new document. This buffer needs to be at least=20
    <B>ODM_DOCID_MAX</B> bytes in length. If successful then a =
Null-terminated=20
    document ID will be returned here, unless the document is saved with =
the=20
    current ID. In this case the first byte of this buffer will be set =
to Null=20
    and 0 will be returned. Otherwise the contents of the buffer will be =

    undefined. </P>
    <P><I>lpszFormat </I>- in - A Null-terminated string naming the =
format in=20
    which the application expects to save the document. This may be =
passed as a=20
    parameter to the </P>
    <P><I>pcbCallBack</I> function which may return a different format.=20
    pcbCallBack - in - A pointer to a callback function that can be used =
by the=20
    application to make other saving options available to the user. Any =
UI=20
    presented by this callback function should be task modal. The =
function=20
    should return a pointer to a format string which may or may not be =
the same=20
    as the original format string. This parameter may be null if the =
application=20
    does not wish to present any options. Under Microsoft Windows the=20
    procedure-instance address of the callback function (obtained from=20
    MakeProcInstance) should be used. The callback function's interface =
is as=20
    follows: </P>
    <CENTER>
    <P align=3Dcenter><B>LPSTR SaveAsCallBack(DWORD dwEnvData, LPSTR =
lpszFormat,=20
    LPVOID pInstanceData)</B> </P></CENTER>
    <P><I>dwEnvData</I> - in - Environment data. On Windows platforms =
this is a=20
    Window handle for a parent window to associate with the callback =
function's=20
    display. If the DMS displayed a dialog in response to the =
<B>ODMSaveAs</B>=20
    call then it should pass the window handle for that dialog. =
Otherwise it=20
    should pass the window handle obtained from the =
<B>ODMRegisterApp</B> call.=20
    The callback function may use this window handle as the parent =
window for=20
    any dialogs or other windows it displays. </P>
    <P><I>lpszFormat</I> - The currently selected document format. </P>
    <P><I>pInstanceData</I> - The instance data passed from the calling=20
    application. </P>
    <P><I>pInstanceData</I> - in - A pointer to caller context =
information that=20
    will be passed to the <I>pcbCallBack</I> function. This data will =
not be=20
    accessed by ODMA. </P>
    <P><B>Return value:</B> 0 if successful. <B>ODM_E_CANCEL</B> if the =
user=20
    cancels the creation of the new document. <B>ODM_E_DOCID</B> if the =
document=20
    ID is invalid or refers to a document that no longer exists.=20
    <B>ODM_E_FAIL</B> if the DMS is unable to create the new document.=20
    <B>ODM_E_HANDLE</B> if odmHandle was invalid. <B>ODM_E_APPSELECT</B> =
if the=20
    user selected to save the document as a non-profiled document. </P>
    <H4><FONT color=3Dmaroon>ODMActivate </FONT></H4>
    <H5>ODMSTATUS ODMActivate( ODMHANDLE odmHandle, WORD action, LPSTR =
lpszDocId=20
    ) </H5>
    <P>This function causes the DMS to perform actions that do not =
require=20
    cooperation from the calling application. Control is returned to the =
calling=20
    application after the specified action has been completed. Note that =
a DMS=20
    is not required to support all of these actions. </P>
    <P><FONT color=3Dteal>Parameters:</FONT> </P>
    <P><I>odmHandle</I> - in - An ODMA handle obtained by a previous =
call to=20
    <B>ODMRegisterApp</B>. </P>
    <P>action - in - One of the following action codes: </P>
    <UL>
      <LI><B>ODM_NONE</B> - No specific action is requested. The DMS =
should=20
      simply make itself visible and let the user select the action to =
be=20
      performed.=20
      <LI><B>ODM_DELETE</B> - The DMS should delete the specified =
document. Note=20
      that most DMSs will not allow a deletion to occur if the document =
is=20
      currently in use. Normally the application would call ODMSelectDoc =
to get=20
      a document ID for the document to be deleted.=20
      <LI><B>ODM_SHOWATTRIBUTES</B> - The DMS should display the =
specified=20
      document's profile or attributes.=20
      <LI><B>ODM_EDITATTRIBUTES</B> - The DMS should display the =
specified=20
      document's profile or attributes, and the user should be put in =
edit mode.=20
      Note that some DMSs will not allow a document's attributes to be =
edited=20
      while the document is in use.=20
      <LI><B>ODM_VIEWDOC </B>- The DMS should display the specified =
document in=20
      a viewer window.=20
      <LI><B>ODM_OPENDOC</B> - The DMS should open the specified =
document in its=20
      native application. This function is intended for use by =
applications=20
      other than the document's native application (e-mail, workflow,=20
      annotation, etc.). Applications should use ODMOpenDoc to access =
their own=20
      documents. </LI></UL>
    <P><I>lpszDocId</I> - in - A document ID specifying the document on =
which to=20
    perform the requested action. This parameter may be Null if the =
action is=20
    <B>ODM_NONE</B>. </P>
    <P><B>Return value</B>: 0 if successful. <B>ODM_E_DOCID</B> if the =
document=20
    ID is invalid or refers to a document that no longer exists.=20
    <B>ODM_E_INUSE</B> if the document is currently in use orchecked out =
by=20
    another user on actions where this would preclude the operation from =

    completing correctly. <B>ODM_E_CANCEL</B> if the action was canceled =
by the=20
    user. <B>ODM_E_ITEM</B> if action is invalid or not supported by the =
DMS.=20
    <B>ODM_E_FAIL</B> if the action could not be completed by the DMS.=20
    <B>ODM_E_HANDLE</B> if odmHandle was invalid. </P>
    <H4><FONT color=3Dmaroon>ODMGetDocInfo</FONT> </H4>
    <H5>ODMSTATUS ODMGetDocInfo( ODMHANDLE odmHandle, LPSTR lpszDocId, =
WORD=20
    item, LPSTR lpszData, WORD dataLen ) </H5>
    <P>An application can use this function to obtain information about =
a=20
    document from the DMS. </P>
    <H4><FONT color=3Dteal>Parameters</FONT>: </H4>
    <P><I>odmHandle</I> - in - An ODMA handle obtained by a previous =
call to=20
    <B>ODMRegisterApp</B>. </P>
    <P><I>lpszDocId</I> - in - A Null-terminated document ID. This is =
typically=20
    obtained by a call to <B>ODMSelectDoc</B> or <B>ODMNewDoc</B>. The =
specified=20
    document may or may not be open when <B>ODMGetDocInfo</B> is called. =
</P>
    <P><I>item </I>- in - One of the following: </P>
    <UL>
      <LI><B>ODM_AUTHOR</B> - Author of the document.=20
      <LI><B>ODM_NAME</B> - Name of the document. This is a descriptive =
name for=20
      the document, not the filename.=20
      <LI><B>ODM_TYPE</B> - Type of the document. This is typically an=20
      indication of the format or content of the document, i.e. =
correspondence,=20
      memo, contract, etc.=20
      <LI><B>ODM_TITLETEXT</B> - Suggested text to display in the =
document=20
      window's title bar. This may include one or more fields from the=20
      document's profile and possibly other information as well.=20
      <LI><B>ODM_CONTENTFORMAT</B> - The format string indicating the =
format of=20
      the document's content.=20
      <LI><B>ODM_DMS_DEFINED</B> - The lpszData parameter contains a=20
      DMS-specific indication of the data to be returned. Note that an=20
      application must know which DMS it is talking to and must =
understand the=20
      data indications supported by that DMS in order to use this item =
name.=20
      </LI></UL>
    <P><I>lpszData </I>- in/out - On input, ignored if item is anything =
other=20
    than <B>ODM_DMS_DEFINED</B>. If item is <B>ODM_DMS_DEFINED</B> then =
lpszData=20
    contains an indication of the data to be returned. On output, the =
requested=20
    data is returned in the buffer pointed to by lpszData. </P>
    <P><I>dataLen</I> - in - length of the output buffer pointed to by =
lpszData.=20
    If the data to be returned is longer than this, it will be =
truncated. In=20
    either case the returned data will always be terminated with a Null=20
    character. </P>
    <P><B>Return value:</B> 0 if successful. <B>ODM_E_DOCID</B> if the =
document=20
    ID is invalid or refers to a document that no longer exists.=20
    <B>ODM_E_ITEM</B> if item is invalid or not supported by the =
document's DMS.=20
    <B>ODM_E_HANDLE</B> if odmHandle was invalid. </P>
    <H4><FONT color=3Dmaroon>ODMSetDocInfo</FONT> </H4>
    <H5>ODMSTATUS ODMSetDocInfo( ODMHANDLE odmHandle, LPSTR lpszDocId, =
WORD=20
    item, LPSTR lpszData ) </H5>
    <P>An application can use this function to pass information about =
the=20
    document to the DMS. The DMS may or may not accept the information; =
most=20
    DMSs validate attributes like document types and authors against =
predefined=20
    tables. </P>
    <H4><FONT color=3Dteal>Parameters: </FONT></H4>
    <P><I>odmHandle</I> - in - An ODMA handle obtained by a previous =
call to=20
    <B>ODMRegisterApp</B>. </P>
    <P><I>lpszDocId</I> - in - A Null-terminated document ID. This is =
typically=20
    obtained by a call to <B>ODMSelectDoc</B> or <B>ODMNewDoc</B>. The =
specified=20
    document may or may not be open when <B>ODMSetDocInfo</B> is =
called.</P>
    <P><I>item</I>-in- One of the following: <B></B></P>
    <UL>
      <LI><B>ODM_AUTHOR</B> - Author of the document.=20
      <LI><B>ODM_NAME </B>- Name of the document. This is a descriptive =
name for=20
      the document, not the filename.=20
      <LI><B>ODM_TYPE </B>- Type of the document. This is typically an=20
      indication of the format or content of the document, i.e. =
correspondence,=20
      memo, contract, etc.=20
      <LI><B>ODM_CONTENTFORMAT </B>- The document's format string. Note =
that=20
      this merely informs the DMS of a change in the document's format; =
it does=20
      not cause a conversion process to take place within the DMS.=20
      <LI><B>ODM_DMS_DEFINED</B> - The lpszData parameter contains a=20
      DMS-specific indication of the data being passed as well as the =
data=20
      itself. Note that an application must know which DMS it is talking =
to and=20
      must understand the data indications supported by that DMS in =
order to use=20
      this item name. </LI></UL>
    <P><I>lpszData </I>- in - the data being passed to the DMS. Must be=20
    null-terminated. </P>
    <P><B>Return value</B>: 0 if successful. <B>ODM_E_DOCID</B> if the =
document=20
    ID is invalid or refers to a document that no longer exists.=20
    <B>ODM_E_ITEM</B> if item is invalid. <B>ODM_E_HANDLE</B> if =
odmHandle was=20
    invalid. <B>ODM_E_FAIL</B> if the specified data was invalid or the =
DMS was=20
    unable to accept it for other reasons. </P>
    <H4>ODMGetDMSInfo </H4>
    <H5>ODMSTATUS ODMGetDMSInfo( ODMHANDLE odmHandle, LPSTR lpszDmsId, =
LPWORD=20
    pwVerNo, LPDWORD pdwExtensions ) </H5>
    <P>This function returns information to the application about the =
currently=20
    active DMS. </P>
    <H4><FONT color=3Dteal>Parameters:</FONT> </H4>
    <P><I>odmHandle </I>- in - An ODMA handle obtained by a previous =
call to=20
    <B>ODMRegisterApp</B>. </P>
    <P><I>lpszDmsId</I> - out - This should point to an area at least=20
    <B>ODM_DMID_MAX</B> bytes long. A Null-terminated ID identifying the =
DMS is=20
    returned here. This is the same ID embedded in document IDs returned =
by this=20
    DMS. </P>
    <P><I>pwVerNo</I> - out - The version of the ODMA API supported by =
this DMS=20
    is returned here. </P>
    <P><I>pdwExtensions</I> - out - Indications of extensions to the =
base ODMA=20
    API that are supported by this DMS are returned here. No extensions =
have=20
    been defined yet, so currently 0 will always be returned here. </P>
    <P><B>Return value</B>: 0 if successful. <B>ODM_E_HANDLE</B> if =
odmHandle=20
    was invalid. </P>
    <H4><FONT color=3Dmaroon>ODMQueryInterface</FONT> </H4>
    <H5>HRESULT ODMQueryInterface( ODMHANDLE odmHandle, LPSTR lpszDocId, =
REFIID=20
    riid, LPVOID FAR *ppvObj ) </H5>
    <P>An application can use this function to get a COM interface from =
an ODMA=20
    provider. All ODMA providers support the <B>IODMDocMan</B> =
interface, and=20
    individual DMSs may support other interfaces as well. Note that this =

    function is prototyped in odmacom.h instead of odma.h, so that =
non-COM-aware=20
    applications do not have to #include the header files that define =
interface=20
    IDs. </P>
    <H4><FONT color=3Dteal>Parameters:</FONT> </H4>
    <P><I>odmHandle</I> - in - An ODMA handle obtained by a previous =
call to=20
    <B>ODMRegisterApp</B>. </P>
    <P><I>lpszDocId</I> - in - An ODMA document ID or Null. If Null then =
the=20
    application's default DMS is queried for the interface. Otherwise =
the DMS=20
    that created this document ID is queried. </P>
    <P><I>riid</I> - in - The interface to be obtained from the DMS. =
</P>
    <P><I>ppvObj</I> - out - If the requested interface is supported by =
the DMS=20
    then it is returned here. Otherwise ppvObj is set to Null. </P>
    <P><B>Return value</B>: S_OK if successful. E_INVALIDARG if =
odmHandle or=20
    lpszDocId is invalid. E_NOINTERFACE if the requested interface is =
not=20
    supported by the DMS. </P>
    <H4><FONT color=3Dmaroon>ODMGetLeadMoniker </FONT></H4>
    <H5>ODMSTATUS ODMGetLeadMoniker( ODMHANDLE odmHandle, LPSTR =
lpszDocId,=20
    LPMONIKER FAR *ppMoniker ) </H5>
    <P>Applications that are OLE 2 servers typically form composite =
monikers for=20
    their OLE links by combining a file moniker representing the =
document with=20
    one or more item monikers representing a particular section of the =
document.=20
    This approach often does not work in environments where document =
management=20
    systems are in use because the filename that the application sees is =
usually=20
    just temporary. This function lets the application obtain a leading =
moniker=20
    from the DMS that can be used in place of the file moniker. </P>
    <P>This function will only be available on platforms supporting OLE =
2. This=20
    function may not be supported by some DMSs; those DMSs will return=20
    <B>ODM_E_FAIL.</B> In this case the application should go ahead and =
use the=20
    file moniker as though ODMA were not present. Note that this =
function is=20
    prototyped in odmacom.h instead of odma.h, so that non-OLE-aware=20
    applications do not have to #include the OLE header files. </P>
    <H4><FONT color=3Dteal>Parameters:</FONT> </H4>
    <P><I>odmHandle</I> - in - An ODMA handle obtained by a previous =
call to=20
    <B>ODMRegisterApp</B>. </P>
    <P><I>lpszDocId</I> - in - An ODMA document ID. </P>
    <P><I>ppMoniker </I>- out - A leading moniker for the specified =
document ID=20
    will be returned here if successful. Otherwise Null will be returned =
here.=20
    </P>
    <P><B>Return value</B>: 0 if successful. <B>ODM_E_FAIL</B> if the =
DMS that=20
    created the specified document ID does not support OLE moniker =
building.=20
    <B>ODM_E_DOCID</B> if the document ID is invalid or refers to a =
document=20
    that no longer exists. <B>ODM_E_HANDLE</B> if odmHandle is invalid. =
</P>
    <P>&nbsp;</P>
    <H3><FONT color=3Dteal>DMS Interface</FONT> </H3>
    <P>A DMS interfaces with ODMA through a function called =
ODMGetODMInterface=20
    and through COM interfaces. When an application calls the ODMA =
connection=20
    manager's ODMRegisterApp function, the connection manager calls the=20
    appropriate DMS's ODMGetODMInterface function to establish a =
connection with=20
    the DMS. This function is defined as follows: </P>
    <P><B><FONT color=3Dmaroon>ODMGetODMInterface </FONT></B></P>
    <P>HRESULT ODMGetODMInterface( REFIID riid, LPVOID FAR *ppvObj, =
LPUNKNOWN=20
    pUnkOuter, LPVOID pReserved, LPSTR lpszAppId, DWORD dwEnvData ) </P>
    <P>The ODMA connection manager calls this function to get an =
interface from=20
    a DMS. This function is not available to ODMA-aware applications. =
</P>
    <H4><FONT color=3Dteal>Parameters</FONT>: </H4>
    <P><I>riid </I>- in - ID of the interface being requested. This will =

    typically be <B>IID_IODMDocMan</B>, but the connection manager may =
also pass=20
    through calls for other interfaces from the client. ODMA providers =
must=20
    support the <B>IID_IODMDocMan</B> interface. </P>
    <P><I>ppvObj</I> - out - The requested interface should be returned =
here. If=20
    the DMS cannot return the requested interface, ppvObj should be set =
to Null.=20
    </P>
    <P><I>pUnkOuter</I> - in - The controlling IUnknown interface for =
the=20
    aggregate object. ODMA providers must support aggregation. </P>
    <P><I>pReserved </I>- in - Reserved for future use. Will always be =
set to=20
    Null. </P>
    <P><I>lpszAppId</I> - in - The ID of the calling application. See=20
    <B>ODMRegisterApp</B>. </P>
    <P><I>dwEnvData</I> - in - Environment specific data. On Windows =
platforms=20
    this will be a window handle from the calling application. See=20
    <B>ODMRegisterApp</B>. </P>
    <P><B>Return value</B>: S_OK if successful. <B>E_NOINTERFACE</B> if =
the=20
    requested interface is not supported. </P>
    <H3><FONT color=3Dteal>Binding to the API under Windows 3.x, Windows =
95 and=20
    Windows NT </FONT></H3>
    <P>The ODMA connection manager, <B>ODMA.DLL</B> (Windows 3.x) or=20
    <B>ODMA32.DLL</B> (Windows 95 and NT), and a corresponding link =
library,=20
    <B>ODMA.LIB</B> (Windows 3.x) or <B>ODMA32.LIB</B> (Windows 95 and =
NT), will=20
    be made freely available to any application vendor wishing to use =
them.=20
    Applications can choose either of the methods described below to =
bind to=20
    ODMA: </P>
    <OL>
      <LI>Link to <B>ODMA.LIB/ODMA32.LIB</B>. Applications choosing this =

      approach will need to install a copy of <B>ODMA.DLL/ODMA32.DLL</B> =
into=20
      the Windows system directory at the time the application is =
installed=20
      unless a newer copy of <B>ODMA.DLL/ODMA32.DLL</B> already resides =
there.=20
      At startup time the application can call ODMRegisterApp to =
determine=20
      whether or not an ODMA provider is present for the calling =
application.=20
      Dynamically load <B>ODMA.DLL/ODMA32.DLL</B> at startup time with a =
call to=20
      LoadLibrary. With this approach the application has to call =
GetProcAddress=20
      to get a pointer to each ODMA function it will call, but the =
application=20
      does not have to do anything related to ODMA at installation time. =
If=20
      <B>ODMA.DLL/ODMA32.DLL</B> doesn't exist or if ODMRegisterApp =
returns=20
      ODM_E_NODMS then the application knows that no ODMA provider is =
present=20
      for the calling application. </LI></OL>
    <P>There is currently no thunk layer that exists to allow a 32 bit=20
    application and a 16 bit DMS, or vise versa, to interact with each =
other.=20
    </P>
    <H3><FONT color=3Dteal>Installing a DMS under Windows 3.x, Windows =
95 and=20
    Windows NT</FONT> </H3>
    <P>The ODMA connection manager, <B>ODMA.DLL</B> for Windows 3.x and=20
    <B>ODMA32.DLL</B> for Windows NT and Windows 95, will be provided to =
all DMS=20
    vendors that want to support the ODMA specification. These DLLs will =
serve=20
    as a common entry point for applications that wish to call ODMA =
functions.=20
    Its implementation of <B>ODMRegisterApp</B> will figure out which =
DMS is=20
    registered for default use by the calling application. It will then =
load the=20
    appropriate DMS's DLL and pass through the function call. All other =
ODMA=20
    function calls that do not include a document ID will be passed to =
this=20
    default DMS. </P>
    <P>When an ODMA call is made that includes a document ID, the ODMA=20
    connection manager will determine which DMS created the ID. If that =
DMS has=20
    not been initialized yet by the calling application, the connection =
manager=20
    will call the provider's <B>ODMGetODMInterface</B> function and will =
then=20
    pass through the current ODMA function call.</P>
    <P>As part of its installation, a DMS should check whether a copy of =

    <B>ODMA.DLL</B> or <B>ODMA32.DLL</B> already exists in the Windows =
system=20
    directory. If it does not or if the DMS has a newer version then it =
should=20
    copy its version of <B>ODMA.DLL</B> or ODMA32.DLL to the Windows =
system=20
    directory. Then it should register with the ODMA connection manager =
by=20
    adding one or more keys to the registration database. </P>
    <P>Each DMS must add a subkey to the root level ODMA key. This =
subkey should=20
    be named the same as the DMS's DMS ID, and the subkey's value should =
specify=20
    the location of the DLL containing the DMS's ODMA entry points. For =
example,=20
    suppose a DMS with a DMS ID of DDD implemented its ODMA entry points =
in=20
    H:\ABC\XYZ.DLL. It would add the following key and value to the =
registration=20
    database: </P>
    <P>ODMA\DDD =3D H:\ABC\XYZ.DLL for Windows 3.x </P>
    <P>ODMA32\DDD =3D H:\ABC\XYZ.DLL for Win32 (i.e. WindowsNT and =
Windows95) </P>
    <P>If the DMS wanted to serve as the default ODMA provider to be =
used with=20
    all ODMA-aware applications that were not registered with a specific =
DMS, it=20
    would add the DEFAULT subkey to its DMS ID key as shown below: </P>
    <P>ODMA\DDD\DEFAULT for Windows 3.x </P>
    <P>ODMA32\DDD\DEFAULT for Win32 (i.e. WindowsNT and Windows95) </P>
    <P>If the DMS wanted to specifically register itself as the ODMA =
provider=20
    for one or more applications, it would also add a subkey to the =
relevant=20
    applications' root level keys. Note that this is only necessary if a =

    different DMS is registered as the default ODMA provider. Each time =
an=20
    application calls <B>ODMRegisterApp</B>, the connection manager =
looks in the=20
    registration database for a root-level key that matches the =
specified=20
    application ID. If it finds such a key then it looks under it for a =
subkey=20
    called ODMA. The value of this key is the DMS ID of the specifically =

    registered DMS. If the application ID key is not found or if the =
subkey ODMA=20
    or ODMA32 does not exist under it, the connection manager looks at =
the=20
    subkeys of the root-level key ODMA or ODMA32 for a default ODMA=20
    implementation.</P>
    <P>For example, suppose a document management system with a DMS ID =
of DDD=20
    wanted to support only one particular application that used QQQ as =
its=20
    application ID. It would add the following key and value to the =
registration=20
    database in addition to the ODMA subkey described above: </P>
    <P>QQQ\ODMA =3D DDD for Windows 3.x </P>
    <P>QQQ\ODMA32 =3D DDD for Win32 (i.e. WindowsNT and Windows95) </P>
    <P>&nbsp;</P>
    <CENTER>
    <H2><FONT color=3Dmaroon>Appendix</FONT> </H2></CENTER>
    <CENTER>
    <H4 align=3Dcenter>A Preferred Call Usage for Initial File Creation=20
    </H4></CENTER>
    <P>There has been some misunderstandings among both DMS and =
application=20
    vendors on the correct use of the ODMA calls to initially create a =
file.=20
    This appendix is basically from a proposal made in October 1994 by =
Rod=20
    Schiffman of Novell. There has been no dissension on the issue since =
the=20
    original proposal was made. Until the standard is modified to =
provide other=20
    methods for the initial creation of a new document in a DMS, this =
provides a=20
    sequence for the calls that will work with all major DMS vendors. =
</P>
    <P>It is probably useful for me to describe the terminology and =
concepts I=20
    will use in this discussion. A DMS is fundamentally more complex =
than my=20
    description, but it will suffice for my purposes. A DMS is a black =
box that=20
    manages documents. My Local System is the particular machine and =
Operating=20
    System, or Environment, that I use. It has its own file system, =
applications=20
    and interfaces. When I need to do something to a existing document =
in the=20
    DMS, I select it using tools the DMS provides and retrieve it into =
my local=20
    system. I use an application to perform operations on the document. =
I may=20
    want to create a new document with my application. The new document =
will be=20
    stored on my local system until I save it into the DMS. The DMS may =
want to=20
    tell me where I should save it on the Local System until I =
eventually save=20
    it into the DMS. I may also want to update the copy in the DMS while =
I am=20
    still working on it. I call this writing the document through to the =
DMS.=20
    When I am finally done working on the document, I can save it to the =
DMS. It=20
    is then closed. At some point in the process of creating a new =
document, the=20
    DMS will require me to give it a profile. When I have saved the =
document to=20
    the DMS, it is closed and the document no longer has a presence on =
my local=20
    machine. ODMA has a vaguely defined concept of formats that are =
attached to=20
    a document, and while the timing of when and how formats are defined =
plays a=20
    central role in this discussion, formats, conversions and their =
association=20
    to documents does not play a role in this discussion. </P>
    <P>ODMSaveDoc is the only ODMA function that actually saves a =
document into=20
    a DMS. It uses a Document ID (DocID) supplied by the DMS. The =
initial=20
    creation of the first DocID for the document can only be supplied by =

    ODMNewDoc. ODMSaveAs and ODMSaveDoc can return a new DocID, but they =
must=20
    already have an initial DocID to start with. ODMSelectDoc only =
returns a=20
    DocID that already exists. This means that ODMNewDoc must be called =
to=20
    generate the initial DocID. After the application has a DocID, it =
can call=20
    ODMOpenDoc to get a local file name to save the document to and =
ODMSaveDoc=20
    to write the document through to the DMS. This would imply that it =
is not=20
    necessary to call ODMSaveAs in the process of saving the document =
the first=20
    time. This has caused a number of people to assume that the usage of =

    ODMNewDoc was synonymous with the initial =93Save=94 function in =
most=20
    applications. However, the spec says that the format specified in =
ODMNewDoc=20
    =93may be changed later via an ODMSaveAs call.=94 This implies that =
it is OK to=20
    call ODMSaveAs after calling ODMNewDoc. ODMSaveAs is the only call =
that=20
    allows an application to interact with the DMS and supply =
application=20
    specific information such as formats and passwords. If an app only =
calls=20
    ODMNewDoc and does not call ODMSaveAs, it loses the ability to =
provide=20
    application specific information. ODMSaveAs requires that a user =
interface=20
    is supplied to the user. If ODMNewDoc also supplies a user =
interface, then=20
    the user interface comes up twice for each document creation. Once =
in=20
    ODMNewDoc and again in ODMSaveAs. This is probably not something =
that the=20
    user wants. Also, how do we reconcile the ability to call ODMNewDoc =
without=20
    a user interface. If ODMNewDoc is called with no user interface and =
a DocID=20
    is returned, then when is the profile filled in? ODMOpenDoc and =
ODMSaveDoc=20
    and ODMCloseDoc have no obvious provisions for providing a user =
interface.=20
    </P>
    <P>ODMNewDoc was originally intended to be synonymous with the =
=93New=94 menu=20
    choice, not the =93Save=94 menu choice, in most applications. For =
example,=20
    although SoftSolutions and PC Docs do not care about a document =
until it is=20
    time to save it to the DMS the first time, DEC TeamLinks does have =
the=20
    concept of letting the DMS know a document is going through initial=20
    creation. There is nothing in the spec that indicates whether =
ODMNewDoc=20
    should be called at document creation or just before saving the =
document the=20
    first time. This is not an accident according to Brad Clements, the =
original=20
    author of the ODMA spec. It can be done at whatever time makes sense =
for the=20
    DMS and application. ODMNewDoc does not have provisions for the =
callback=20
    routine because it notifies the DMS about the creation of a document =
not the=20
    saving of a document. At document creation time, the user is =
probably not=20
    worried about the what the final format will be or if there will be =
a=20
    password. The user may not, and this is crucial, even save the =
document to=20
    the DMS. It is possible that if ODMNewDoc is called without a user=20
    interface, that the DocID returned to the application may not =
eventually be=20
    used, if the user is allowed to have the file saved to the local =
file system=20
    in a later call to ODMSaveAs. </P>
    <P>It turns out that many applications and Document Management =
Systems do=20
    not have or need a concept of providing application and DMS =
interaction=20
    until the document is ready to be saved in the DMS for the first =
time.=20
    Certainly a DMS must deal with applications that will not provide =
any=20
    interaction with the DMS until the document is already created in =
the edit=20
    buffer and is ready to be saved. At this point I would like to point =
out a=20
    scenario that follows the spec, and still works with major =
applications that=20
    may not have followed the spec according to the interpretation given =
here.=20
    </P>
    <P>At the time of initial document creation, or when it is time to =
save the=20
    document the application should call ODMNewDoc with the ODM_SILENT =
flag.=20
    This will return a temporary DocID that the application can use.=20
    Technically, the application could call ODMOpenDoc to have a local =
temporary=20
    file to use until the document is finally saved into the DMS, but I =
know=20
    that every DMS vendor I have talked to would frown on this idea. =
They prefer=20
    the idea that all saves are written through to the DMS and that =
there is a=20
    full profile for anything that exists in the DMS. It is OK for the =
DMS=20
    vendor require this by returning an ODM_E_USERINT error to indicate =
that=20
    ODMOpenDoc cannot be called until the app makes a call to ODMNewDoc =
or=20
    ODMSaveAs that brings up an user interface. This implies that the=20
    application would be better to avoid the situation and not call =
ODMOpenDoc=20
    until after an user interface is provided to the user. After calling =

    ODMNewDoc in silent mode, take the DocID that is returned and call =
ODMSaveAs=20
    to have the profile created, and allow access to the callback =
routines. If=20
    the ODMNewDoc returns an ODM_E_USERINT error because it does not =
support the=20
    silent mode, then call ODMNewDoc with a user interface and skip =
calling=20
    ODMSaveAs. This performs the same functionality, but does not =
provide access=20
    to the callback routines. If the application still wants the user to =
see the=20
    callback dialog, then it can call the callback dialog itself after =
calling=20
    the ODMNewDoc call. This is not optimal, but does work. In either =
case the=20
    user interface is only presented to the user one time. </P>
    <P>There are a couple caveats for DMS vendors. The DocID returned by =

    ODMNewDoc must be a temporary ID. It is possible that the user will =
throw=20
    away the file before it is saved, or that it will be saved to the =
native OS=20
    through the options button in the SaveAs dialog. This could be =
easily=20
    handled by returning a well known dummy value like ::ODMA\&lt;app=20
    id&gt;\NULLWhen ODMSaveAs sees this null value as the DocID, it can =
know=20
    that it is creating the document for the first time and take =
appropriate=20
    action as opposed to the normal SaveAs action. It does not matter if =
there=20
    are multiple documents using this DocID at the same time as long as =
the DMS=20
    returns ODM_E_USERINT to the ODMOpenDoc call that passed in the null =
DocID.=20
    </P>
    <P>Basically, this turns the ODMNewDoc into a fancy NOP routine. =
There may=20
    be situations where this may not be the best action, but since there =
is no=20
    compelling reason for the existence of the ODMNewDoc call in the 1.0 =
spec,=20
    it seems to solve more problems than it creates. It would probably =
be a good=20
    idea to add an extension to the 1.0 spec in ODMA 1.1 where the =
ODMSaveAs=20
    call can allow a NULL to be passed in as the lpszDocID parameter to =
indicate=20
    that the document is being saved for the first time. This would free =
the=20
    application from having to use the ODMNewDoc call. Of course, that =
is what=20
    the addition of a dummy DocID value returned from ODMNewDoc =
accomplishes. In=20
    the ODMA 1.1 time frame a new ODMNewDoc call can be created if =
someone comes=20
    up with a compelling reason for its existence. Simply using the =
ODMSaveAs=20
    call when an application is creating a new file in the DMS, whether =
it is=20
    the first save or an actual SaveAs, matches the way most =
applications work=20
    today. </P></LI></UL></BLOCKQUOTE>
<P></P>
